  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This activity is criminalized because it facilitates and encourages other illegal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, terrorism financing, and fraud.\n\nIn China, the government has established robust legal frameworks and regulatory mechanisms to combat money laundering. The Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China, along with other related regulations, explicitly prohibits and penalizes money laundering activities. The Chinese government is committed to maintaining financial security and social stability by actively preventing and cracking down on such illegal activities in accordance with the law.",
